DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260702
SUMMARY:Deadline: Light Work Artist-in-Residence 2027 (Syracuse\, NY)
DESCRIPTION:Light Work\, an independent non-profit founded in 1973\, offers
  a long-running artist-in-residence programme dedicated to the development
  of experimental and contemporary photographic practices. Over 400 artists
  have participated in the residency\, with many going on to gain internati
 onal recognition. ELIGIBILITY: artists working in photography or image-bas
 ed media\, from any country and at any career stage. Apply via the Light W
 ork SlideRoom portal.\n\nOrganisation: Light Work\nLocation: Syracuse\, Ne
 w York\, USA (in-person\, one-month residency on site)\nAward: $7\,500 sti
 pend plus a furnished apartment and access to state-of-the-art photography
  facilities. The residency concludes with a feature in a special edition o
 f 'Contact Sheet: The Light Work Annual' alongside a commissioned essay. N
 o application fee.\nDuration: One-month residency in 2027\n\nMore: https:/
 /lightwork.slideroom.com
URL:https://lightwork.slideroom.com
LOCATION:Syracuse\, New York\, USA (in-person\, one-month residency on site
 )
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:the-lab-living-wage-residencies-2026-27@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260520T085057Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260531
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260601
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Lab: Living Wage Residencies 2026-27 (San Francisco)
DESCRIPTION:The Lab's flagship Living Wage Residency\, a substantial in-per
 son residency in San Francisco's Mission District for artists working in a
 ny media and discipline. Since 2014 the programme has directed over USD 1 
 million to artists\, with artist fees representing nearly 30% of The Lab's
  average operating budget. The Lab's history is as a site for experimental
  and interdisciplinary work spanning performance\, exhibition\, installati
 on\, sound and experimental music\, writing\, institutional critique\, soc
 ial practice\, parades\, feasts and further disciplines yet to be defined.
  The Lab's mission centres traditionally underrepresented artists\, partic
 ularly those identifying as BIPOC\, LGBTQ+\, women\, disabled and/or from 
 economically marginalised backgrounds. ELIGIBILITY: artists based in the S
 an Francisco Bay Area (tight geographic restriction\; in-person access to 
 The Lab's space is central to the residency). SUPPORT per residency: USD 1
 7\,530 artist fee (3 months at a Bay Area living wage per MIT's Living Wag
 e Calculator)\; USD 5\,000 for collaborators and materials\; three months 
 of rehearsal/workshop access to The Lab's space (as available around other
  programming)\; two weeks of continuous use of the exhibition and performa
 nce spaces\; curatorial and marketing support\, outside studio visits\, do
 cumentation and publicity. PROCESS: Stage 1 application (CV\, 3 work links
 \, brief project description and resource plan) due 31 May 2026\; Stage 2 
 invites up to 12 selected artists to develop a full proposal with a USD 25
 0 stipend (Stage 2 deadline TBD). Reviewed by a diverse panel of professio
 nal artists and curators plus The Lab's Board. Outside funding additionall
 y secured for a proposal is not factored into the decision\, but The Lab m
 ay help identify further sources. Supported by the San Francisco Arts Comm
 ission.\n\nOrganisation: The Lab\nLocation: San Francisco Bay Area\, Calif
 ornia\, USA (eligibility restricted to artists based in the Bay Area\; sig
 nificant in-person access to The Lab's space in the Mission District is re
 quired)\nAward: USD 17\,530 artist fee per resident (commensurate with thr
 ee months of work at a San Francisco Bay Area living wage per MIT's Living
  Wage Calculator) plus USD 5\,000 for collaborators and materials. Three m
 onths of rehearsal/workshop access to The Lab's space\, plus two weeks of 
 continuous use of the exhibition and performance spaces for the residency 
 outcome. Curatorial and marketing support\, outside studio visits\, docume
 ntation and publicity. Stage-2 finalists receive an additional USD 250 sti
 pend to develop their full proposal. No application fee.\nDuration: Reside
 ncies take place between July 2026 and June 2027\n\nMore: https://thelabsf
 .notion.site/The-Lab-Living-Wage-Residencies-2026-27-352db69b23b98055ad1de
 7216caf2267
URL:https://thelabsf.notion.site/The-Lab-Living-Wage-Residencies-2026-27-35
 2db69b23b98055ad1de7216caf2267
LOCATION:San Francisco Bay Area\, California\, USA (eligibility restricted 
 to artists based in the Bay Area\; significant in-person access to The Lab
 's space in the Mission District is required)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:nea-grants-for-arts-projects-2026-july@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260520T085057Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260709
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260710
SUMMARY:Deadline: NEA: Grants for Arts Projects (July 2026 cycle)
DESCRIPTION:NEA's flagship project grant for arts organisations across all 
 artistic disciplines. The Grants for Arts Projects (GAP) programme support
 s projects in dance\, design\, folk and traditional arts\, literary arts\,
  local arts agencies\, media arts\, museums\, music\, musical theater\, op
 era\, presenting and multidisciplinary works\, theater\, and visual arts. 
 July 2026 cycle: 'Submit to Grants.gov' deadline 9 July 2026\; portal appl
 ication window 14-21 July 2026. ELIGIBILITY: US non-profits with 501(c)(3)
  status\, units of state or local government\, or federally-recognised tri
 bal communities\; organisations must have a three-year history of programm
 ing and meet a minimum operating budget. Project grants typically USD 10\,
 000 to USD 100\,000+\, with most awards in the USD 10\,000-50\,000 range\;
  a 1:1 cost-share is required. Natural sibling to the NEH Public Humanitie
 s Projects programme on the desk.\n\nOrganisation: National Endowment for 
 the Arts (NEA)\nLocation: United States (eligibility for US non-profits wi
 th 501(c)(3) status\, units of state or local government\, or federally-re
 cognised tribal communities)\nAward: Project grants typically USD 10\,000 
 to USD 100\,000+\, with most awards in the USD 10\,000-50\,000 range\; min
 imum 1:1 cost-share required.\nDuration: Project-based\n\nMore: https://ww
 w.arts.gov/grants/grants-for-arts-projects
URL:https://www.arts.gov/grants/grants-for-arts-projects
LOCATION:United States (eligibility for US non-profits with 501(c)(3) statu
 s\, units of state or local government\, or federally-recognised tribal co
 mmunities)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mats-autumn-2026-fellowship@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260520T085057Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260607
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260608
SUMMARY:Deadline: MATS Autumn 2026 Fellowship (ML Alignment and Theory Scho
 lars)
DESCRIPTION:Fully-funded AI alignment\, security and governance fellowship 
 with mentors from Anthropic\, Google DeepMind\, OpenAI\, Redwood Research 
 and other leading AI safety organisations. Fellows work on a focused resea
 rch project with mentor support during a 10-week in-person programme in Be
 rkeley (28 September - 4 December 2026). New 2026 tracks include Founding/
 Field-Building and Biosecurity in addition to the core alignment\, securit
 y and governance tracks. ELIGIBILITY: open to individual researchers\, bot
 h emerging and experienced\; no specific degree or affiliation required - 
 applications are assessed on research aptitude and track record.\n\nOrgani
 sation: MATS Research\nLocation: Berkeley\, California\, USA (in-person)\n
 Award: USD 5\,000/month stipend plus USD 8\,000/month compute budget\; hou
 sing\, meals and travel covered for the 10-week in-person phase. Approxima
 tely 80% of fellows receive a 6-12 month extension at USD 7\,680/month aft
 er the in-person phase.\nDuration: Ten weeks in-person\, 28 September - 4 
 December 2026 (with extensions for ~80% of fellows)\n\nMore: https://www.m
 atsprogram.org/apply
URL:https://www.matsprogram.org/apply
LOCATION:Berkeley\, California\, USA (in-person)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:neh-public-humanities-projects-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260520T085057Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261015
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261016
SUMMARY:Deadline: NEH: Public Humanities Projects (2026-27 deadlines)
DESCRIPTION:NEH project grants supporting interpretive exhibitions\, histor
 ic-place programming and discussion programmes that bring humanities schol
 arship to public audiences. Aimed at strengthening the humanities in publi
 c life through scholarship-informed public engagement (rather than primary
  research). Two upcoming application windows: 15 October 2026 and 9 Decemb
 er 2026. Two scales: Planning grants up to USD 75\,000\, and Implementatio
 n grants up to USD 1\,000\,000 (most awards substantially smaller than the
  cap). ELIGIBILITY: US-incorporated non-profits with appropriate IRS statu
 s\, libraries\, museums\, historical organisations\, or accredited US coll
 eges and universities\; individual scholars participate as project directo
 rs on behalf of an eligible institution. Aimed at projects that engage bro
 ad public audiences with humanities content (history\, culture\, philosoph
 y\, literature\, etc.).\n\nOrganisation: National Endowment for the Humani
 ties (NEH)\nLocation: United States (applicants must be eligible US non-pr
 ofits - museums\, libraries\, historical organisations\, or accredited US 
 colleges and universities)\nAward: Planning grants up to USD 75\,000\; Imp
 lementation grants up to USD 1\,000\,000 (most awards substantially smalle
 r). Two upcoming deadlines: 15 October 2026 and 9 December 2026.\nDuration
 : Project-based\n\nMore: https://www.neh.gov/grants/public/public-humaniti
 es-projects
URL:https://www.neh.gov/grants/public/public-humanities-projects
LOCATION:United States (applicants must be eligible US non-profits - museum
 s\, libraries\, historical organisations\, or accredited US colleges and u
 niversities)
END:VEVENT
